<h2>Colors</h2>
<h3>Primary Color</h3>
<div class="palette-container">
    <div class="primary">
      <div class="lightest"></div>
      <div class="lighter"></div>
      <div class="darker"></div>
      <div class="darkest"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="description">
      <h4>npm red</h4>
      <p>The color of ripe, juicy persimmons which us wombats love to eat. The color of a warm, furry embrace inside of a darkened log under the dense eucalyptus canopy.</p>
      <p>We currenty use the instantly-recognizable npm red for many CTAs (calls to action), active tab highlghts and indication of link state. It also provides a background to header and footer elements of a most distinctive nature.</p>
      <p>We must be careful when we connatate the use of similar red with danger or error, as not to confuse skittish hoomans.</p>
    </div>
 </div>
<h3>Secondary Color</h3>
<div class="palette-container">
  <div class="secondary">
      <div class="lightest"></div>
      <div class="lighter"></div>
      <div class="darker"></div>
      <div class="darkest"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="description">
    <h4>midnight blue </h4>
    <p>As the sun has set o'er the billabong long ago, the night sky illumniates with a glory of stars in the Southern Hemipshere sky.</p>
    <p>Our complimentary blue is deep enough to balance the contrast of the stark red. Midnight blue is currently in use merely as a background color, something to provide distinction and maturity to our product offerings.</p>
    <p>However, we must be careful ne'er to try to use this alongside the red for interaction elements, lest the color-challenged hoomans have to make distinctions betwixt the two.</p>
  </div>
</div>

